Description: Complete seal-impression, the fine brown Nile clay has some mica inclusions and was hardened after excavation. The rear shows two sides with each two coils of basketry, differing slightly in style, suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and the lid of a basket. The top shows finger impressions and an oval scarab-like seal-impression. Visible is a standing figure with head of bull on the right, facing to the left a cartouche, which is preserved only in fragments, it seems to have a head of captured enemy at the top. At the bottom two horizontal lines.
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Amara West (Nubia), E14.7 temple magazine
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
